\chapter{Households}
\label{chap:households} \index{households}
%#############################################################
\epigraph{There is nothing like staying at home for real comfort.}{Jane Austen}

Equation \ref{eq:IPARC} and Chapters~\ref{chap:introduction}--\ref{chap:carbon_intensity}
developed a framework for sustainability thinking. 
This chapter is the first of four chapters to apply that framework to some
areas of life where sustainability challenges are relevant and important. 
The areas are selected based, in part, on where energy
is consumed (Figure \ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey}), that is, 
the drivers of carbon emissions (Table \ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}).
This chapter (Chapter~\ref{chap:households}) explores 
implications and applications of sustainability thinking
to dwellings.
Transportation (Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation}), 
agriculture (Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}), and
land use and urban planning (Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning})
are the subjects of the next three chapters.
The structure of each chapter in Part \ref{part:sustainability_challenges} is similar:
First, the demand for energy services in a particular area is discussed. 
Next, the drivers for that demand are covered.
Sustainability challenges in that area are examined.
Finally, routes for a transition to a more-sustainable world are considered.

The topic of this chapter, households,
is important for sustainability and stands in contrast to 
the formal employment sector.
With the exception of 
physical plant employees, building managers, and custodial staff, 
few workers 
make decisions about buildings and machines
that affect energy and material resource consumption in offices and factories.

Although ordinary people often have little power to make decisions
with sustainability implications
at work, at school, or at church,
everyone who lives in (or works from) 
a house or apartment 
makes decisions with sustainability implications
in their own household.
Indeed, households are the site for food, water, material, and energy demands.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Households are the site where sustainability meets everyday life.

\end{mcframe}

This chapter focuses on demand for energy in households, 
in keeping with the prime example of the book,
energy consumption and carbon emissions. 
Thus, the first subsection below covers energy demand in households.
Drivers of household energy demand are discussed thereafter.
Next, sustainability challenges associated with CO$_2$ emissions 
from household activities are described.
Sustainability transitions related to households round out the chapter.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for energy in households}
\label{sec:energy_demand_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Households are important for sustainability, 
in part because they are sites of energy consumption.
For example, Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} shows that 
11.9~quads of energy were consumed in U.S.\ residences in 2018,
representing 12\% of final energy consumption.
Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions} shows that CO$_2$ emissions
from the U.S.\ residential sector in 2018 total 
\Sexpr{US_CO2_by_sector$`CO$_2$ emissions [Mt]`[[1]] %>% round(0)}~Mt/year,
predominantly from electricity and natural gas.\index{electricity!consumption!households}
Energy consumption in households is a source of sustainability impacts
(CO$_2$ emissions\index{carbon dioxide (CO$_2$)!emissions of} and 
natural resource extraction\index{natural resources!extraction of})
far beyond the site of the demand.
Thus, decisions made in households have sustainability implications
far beyond the walls of each abode.

However, per-dwelling energy consumption has been rather flat from the 1970 onward.
Increasing energy efficiency of appliances and improvements to building envelopes 
(roof, walls, windows, and base of a dwelling)
has offset rising home sizes.
That said, \emph{total} residential energy consumption has increased,
due to an increase in the total number of dwellings.
Figures~\ref{fig:TotalHouseholdEnergyConsumption}
and~\ref{fig:AverageHouseholdEnergyConsumption}
show these trends.


