From a sustainability point of view,
smaller, more-efficient homes with more occupants
are preferred.
However, trends suggest that although homes are becoming more efficient,
there are more of them, 
they are becoming larger, and
they have fewer occupants on average.


%..............................
\paragraph{Location} 
\label{sec:dwelling_location} \index{households!location}
%..............................

Location of a dwelling is also an important determiner of energy consumption,
not just for the dwelling itself, but also for energy consumed by the residents
for transportation.
(See Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation} for more information on sustainability issues
related to transportation.)
Proximity to work, school, shops, church, and entertainment
makes a significant difference to transportation energy demand.
When buying a home, some purchasers can choose among 
urban, suburban, and rural locations, 
with important sustainability implications.
Living in an urban center can reduce average transport distances. 
Conversely, living in the suburbs or in rural areas can mean
increased fuel use and CO$_2$ emissions for transport. 

Zooming out, the latitude of the home may make a 
larger impact on household sustainability
than the urban/suburban/rural decision.
Homes at high latitudes require heating. 
Homes at low latitudes are often fitted with air conditioning.
Both heating and air conditioning require energy and, 
in today's fossil-fuel-powered world,
cause CO$_2$ to be emitted.
(See Section~\ref{sec:heating_and_cooling} below.)
The climate of mid-latitude locations
can mean \emph{both} heating and air-conditioning are necessary,
potentially increasing the energy required to operate a home in those locations.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Heating and cooling}
\label{sec:heating_and_cooling} \index{households!heating and cooling}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In most locations,
daily and seasonal temperature variations are larger
than the narrow range of temperatures that provide human comfort.
Average daily temperature variations can be in the range of 12~\degC,
and seasonal variations can be 
on the order of 30~\degC~\cite{Experience-Grand-Rapids:vs}.%
\footnote{
   Example temperature variations are for Grand Rapids, Michigan, USA, where
   the average daily high temperature in July is 28~\degC{} and is 
   $-$2~\degC{} in January. 
   Incidentally, the average daily low temperature in January is $-$10~\degC.
}
In contrast, the range of human comfort is between 20 and 23~\degC{} (only 3~\degC), 
depending on humidity and clothing.

Residential heating and cooling reduces the temperature variation
inside a dwelling compared to the outdoors,
providing thermal comfort to the occupants 
to enable work, play, and entertainment.
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that
on average across the U.S.
thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
is the purpose of 
by 54.4\% of all residential energy consumption
(Space heating and space cooling).


%..............................
\paragraph{Building envelope}
\label{sec:building_envelope} \index{building envelope}
%..............................

The purpose of a building envelope
(roof, walls, windows, and base of a dwelling)
is to shield occupants from outside weather and
to maintain dry and comfortable conditions indoors.
The ideal building envelope would
eliminate both heat loss in the winter and heat gain in the summer via
perfect insulation and
windows that neither conduct heat nor pass radiation.
But perfect insulation is not possible, and all windows conduct heat and
pass thermal radiation.
So furnaces\index{furnaces} and air conditioners\index{air conditioners}
replace heat lost in winter and remove heat gained in the summer, respectively.

Windows\index{windows} are an important part of any building's envelope.
They provide natural illumination while shielding occupants from weather.
Like walls and roofs, it is desirable that windows eliminate
heat loss in the winter and heat gain the summer.
However, windows are typically worse insulators than walls and roofs,
owing to thin glazing.


%..............................
\paragraph{Furnaces}
\label{sec:furnaces}\index{furnaces}
%..............................

Furnaces provide space heating,
often from an out-of-the-way location in the dwelling, such as the basement.
Furnaces convert a fuel 
(typically natural gas\index{natural gas} or heating oil\index{heating oil})
into heat by combustion, 
thereby emitting CO$_2$ into the atmosphere.
The heat is delivered to the dwelling via water or air
circulated by a pump or fan.


%..............................
\paragraph{Air conditioners}
\label{sec:air_conditioners}\index{air conditioners}
%..............................

Air conditioners cool and dehumidify indoor air
to provide thermal comfort\index{thermal comfort}
to building occupants in summer.
Most air conditioners consume electricity to perform their cooling function, 
causing CO$_2$ to be emitted from grid-connected fossil-fuel power plants. 
The energy efficiency of air conditioners\index{efficiency!air conditioners}
is quantified by the
Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (SEER),\index{Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (SEER)}
which is
the ratio of cooling provided (in BTU)
to electricity consumed (in W-hr) throughout the season.
Larger SEER values indicate higher efficiency
and lower operating costs compared to lower-SEER air conditioners.

As of 2015, U.S.\ air conditioners must adhere to regionally dependent efficiency standards.
In the southwest, a minimum SEER value of 14 BTU/W-hr is required.
In other parts of the U.S., a minimum SEER value of 13 BTU/W-hr is mandated.
