%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Hygiene}
\label{sec:hygiene}\index{hygiene}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Households consume significant energy and water
for showers, dish washers, toilets, and clothes washers and dryers.
Collectively, these activities may be categorized as ``hygiene.''

Clothes washers and dryers\index{clothes washer}\index{clothes dryer}
consume both water and energy, typically electricity and natural gas.
Burning natural gas emits CO$_2$.
When the electricity for washers and dryers comes from fossil fuel sources, 
further CO$_2$ emissions occur.
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that lighting comprised 4.9\%
of U.S.\ final energy consumption in 2015.

Hygiene is a significant 
cause of energy consumption in the U.S. 
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that hygiene
(Water heating and Laundry) comprised 21.9\%
of U.S.\ final energy consumption in 2015.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Lighting}
\label{sec:lighting}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Indoor lighting provides illumination for rooms,
typically by consuming electricity and emitting CO$_2$ if fossil-fuel sources are used.
Indoor lighting enables work, play, and entertainment
before sunrise and after sunset. 
In many areas of the world, artificial indoor lighting 
extends the economically active portion of the day
several hours beyond daylight hours. 

Artificial interior lighting is a significant 
cause of electricity consumption in most parts of the world. 
Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows that lighting comprised 4.9\%
of U.S.\ final energy consumption in 2015.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability challenges in households}
\label{sec:sustainability_challenges_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%






An interesting tradeoff exists between energy (and CO$_2$) embodied in structures
and energy consumed in daily life.
A home builder \emph{could} install extra insulation,
more than local building codes require.
Doing so \emph{de}creases energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions 
while the home is in use.
However, the home will embody more energy and carbon,
because many insulation types
are energy-intensive to manufacture (especially foam). 







The effectiveness of roof and wall insulation\index{insulation}
is quantified by its R-value\index{R-value},
a measure of the resistance to heat transfer through the insulation material
quantified in units of hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU.
Higher R-values mean less heat is transferred.
Large R-values are achieved with
thicker insulation constructed from low-thermal-conductivity materials.
Halving the amount of heat that passes means doubling the thickness of the 
insulation.
Thicker and thicker layers of insulation are needed to obtain ever-smaller 
fractions of heat transfer reduction. 
Thus, we see that insulation is subject to diminishing returns in its effectiveness
and there is a practical and economic optimum level of insulation.
The Energy Star program recommends levels of roof, wall, and
floor insulation~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:aa}.
In Northern US climates, R-values of 49--60 hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU are recommended.


The insulative properties of windows are quantified by the U-factor\index{U-factor},
which is the inverse of an R-value.
Typical U-factors for windows are 0.2--1.2 BTU/hr-ft$^2$-\degF.
(Corresponding window R-values are 5--0.83 hr-ft$^2$-\degF/BTU.)
Lower U values are more insulative.
Heat gain from solar radiation is quantified by the
solar heat gain coefficient (SHGC)\index{solar heat gain coefficient},
the ratio of solar energy that enters the room to
solar energy incident upon the window.
SHGC values range from 0 to 1,
and lower SHGC values indicate better insulative properties.


Like all energy consumption,
energy consumption for heating and cooling has sustainability implications.
(See Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity}.)
Furnace efficiency\index{efficiency!furnaces} is quantified as
Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency~(AFUE)\index{Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE)},
the percentage of useful heat output
to fuel energy input,
accounting for transient effects during operation
across the year.
Any heat that leaves the home with the exhaust products reduces AFUE.
In the absence of heat lost via exhaust, 
the AFUE rating of a furnace is 100\%.
AFUE is different from (and lower than) steady-state thermal efficiency.
The American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)
\index{American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE)}
publishes Standard 103,
which specifies how AFUE is to be measured~\cite{ASHRAE:vk}.

All furnaces sold in the U.S.\ have an AFUE rating, and
a minimum AFUE rating of 80\% is required
for gas-fired furnaces.\index{furnaces!gas-fired}
%**** Find a good-quality reference for minimum AFUE of 80\% in the U.S. ****
High-efficiency furnaces recover more heat from exhaust gases,
and some reach AFUE values of 98\% or higher.
A tradeoff exists between efficiency and initial cost.
Models with high AFUE are more expensive, initially,
but save money on fuel costs over time.



