\section{Sustainability transitions in households}
\label{sec:sustainability_transitions_households}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%



%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Heating and cooling transition}
\label{sec:heating_cooling_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Greater efficiency can provide the same thermal comfort
with less energy consumed.
Increased residential heating and cooling 
efficiency\index{efficiency!heating and cooling!residential}
(i.e, providing the same comfort with less energy) 
can be obtained
by improving the building envelope or
by improving the efficiency of heating and air conditioning.



%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Hygiene transition}
\label{sec:hygiene_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

To minimize environmental impacts of showering and dish washing,
low-flow showerheads\index{showerheads!low-flow} and faucets\index{faucets}
can be installed.
Low-flow showerheads provide the obvious cost benefit of
reducing water bills.
Also, if less water is consumed,
low-flow showerheads reduce energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions for water heating.
Furthermore, sewerage costs are reduced, because low-flow showerheads
decrease the amount of gray water entering the sewer system (with ``downstream''
energy and cost savings).

Saving water and energy in dish washing can be accomplished by purchasing a
high-efficiency automatic dishwasher.\index{efficiency!dish washers}
The Energy Star program provides 
information about energy-saving dishwashers~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:vn}.
% "According to a recent study by detergent brand Cascade, it takes the average 
% person about 15 seconds to hand-wash a dish. During that time, the sink uses 
% half a gallon of water (a typical faucet spouts four gallons of water every two 
% minutes). By comparison, an Energy Star-certified dishwasher uses less than four
% gallons per cycle, which means running a load with as few as eight dishes can 
% actually save water."
% https://www.bhg.com/kitchen/appliances/dishwasher-save-water/
% Cascade press release: https://news.pg.com/news-releases/news-details/2020/Cascade-Comes-Clean-About-Dishwashing-Habit/default.aspx
%% Perhaps a project to verify their "15 seconds per dish" finding.

To save water consumed by toilets\index{toilets},
displacement and dual-flush systems are recommended.
A displacement system occupies water volume in the tank,
reducing the amount of water used for each flush.
Dual-flush systems provide half- and full-flushes
for disposal of liquids and solids, respectively.

Purchasing washers and dryers with Energy Star\index{Energy Star} ratings can reduce
energy and water consumption by 25\% and 33\%,
respectively~\cite{U.S.-Department-of-Energy:tc, U.S.-Department-of-Energy:vd}.
Energy can be saved by washing clothes less frequently,
using a cold-water cycle, and line drying clothes.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Ligthing transition}
\label{sec:lighting_transition}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

After Edison's invention of the electric light,
filament-based incandescent lighting technology\index{lamps!electric!incandescent}
dominated household lighting.
However, in recent years,
Compact Fluorescent Lights (CFLs)\index{lamps!electric!compact fluorescent (CFL)} and
Light-Emitting Diode (LED)\index{lamps!electric!light emitting diode (LED)}
lamps have revolutionized
the lighting industry and improved lighting efficiency significantly.

In the U.S.\ a transition to LED lamps is well underway,
with incandescent and CFL lamps usually not available in stores.
LED lamps use one-eighth the energy of an equivalent incandescent lamp.%
\footnote{
  A 100-W incandescent lamp gives about 1230~lumens or 12.3~lumens/W.
  A 100-W equivalent LED lamp gives 1200~lumens and consumes only 12~W of electricity,
  for an efficacy of 100~lumens/W.
  The efficacy increase from incandescent to LED lamps is a factor of 8.
}
%
In addition, LED lamps can last up to 10 times longer than incandescent lights.
Higher efficiency and longer life reduce total cost of ownership
of LED bulbs compared to incandescent bulbs by nearly two orders of magnitude.

Of course, the least expensive lamp is the one you don't have to use at all.
Building design techniques such as light harvesting\index{light harvesting}
use natural light to reduce the need for artificial indoor lighting.









%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section*{Summary}
\label{sec:household_summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter identified many sustainability challenges that pertain to households
and decisions made by ordinary people in their homes and apartments.
Energy and material consumption decisions by household residents
drives sustainability in the home. 
Key areas of decision making include
%purchasing and renting,
size and location, 
heating and cooling,
hygiene, and
lighting, 
because many homeowners have agency in these areas of everyday life.

This chapter illustrates two fundamental tradeoffs for stustainability.
The first tradeoff is initial cost (also called capital expense) versus operating cost.
Models or options that are more energy efficient also tend to cost more. 
A larger initial investment pays back by reducing ongoing expenses.
Often the higher initial cost is the result of higher energy and/or material inputs
required to make the more-efficient option.
The second kind of tradeoff is between well-being or affluence and cost. 
Turning the thermostat down means your home is less comfortable, which
means that you are not as well off (not as happy). 
On the other hand, turning the thermostat down saves money, energy, and CO$_2$ emissions.
For both of these kinds of tradeoffs, price is the determiner as to how the tradeoff
plays out. 
Changing society-wide behavior means manipulating prices -- of goods, or energy, or both.

Chapter~\ref{chap:personal_action} provides additional concrete suggestions
for making homes and apartments more sustainable.


