\begin{questions}

\item This chapter covered five important aspects of household sustainability
      (size, location, heating and cooling, hygiene, and lighting).
      Which is \emph{most} important and why?
      What additional areas of household living are important
      from a sustainability point of view?
      
\item What ways can you imagine to re-use or recycle water in a home
      to get closer to a circular economy?

\item \label{question:household_policies} Here are several household-related sustainability policies:
   \begin{enumerate}
      \item require everyone to live in cities like Manhattan (to reduce commuting distances), 
      \item outlaw clothes washers that use hot water (to save CO$_2$ emissions from water heating),
      \item outlaw automatic dishwashers (to reduce energy consumption for water heating),
      \item require all clothes washing to be done at laundromats (to reduce embodied energy of clothes washers in every home),
      \item require all homes to undergo an energy efficiency retrofit before going on the market to be sold
          (to improve energy efficiency of the housing stock),
      \item require all homes to generate solar electricity onsite (to move quickly to a renewable future), and
      \item prohibit clothing made from synthetic fibers (to minimize microplastic pollution).
   \end{enumerate}
      Which of these policies would you welcome? 
      Which would you reject?
      Why?
      
\item Where should you invest in energy efficiency in your home or apartment?

\item Why is nearly every suburban homeowner in the northern U.S.\
      also a Kentucky bluegrass farmer?
      What are the benefits and drawbacks of this arrangement? 
      What are the sustainability implications of this arrangement?
      
\item What are the pros and cons of gardening? Of lawn care? Think, at least,
      in terms of species diversity, emissions/pollution, resource use, affluence,
      and social implications.
      
\item What are ways to increase people per acre and/or people per dwelling?
      In what ways are these the same and how are they different?
      Do you think that dwellings that increase either of these metrics should 
      be incentivized? Why or why not? What are your reasons?
      
\item Externalities are costs born by those who do not receive the benefits of
      an activity. For example, burning natural gas to heat a home releases CO$_2$
      (which harms everyone) and reduces the store of natural resources for future
      generations. Improving a home's energy efficiency, by reducing these externalized
      costs, improves the well being of everyone. Thus, ``all'' of us stand to 
      benefit from energy efficiency. What are some ways to provide resources 
      for deep energy retrofits for those who otherwise couldn't afford to do so?
      What might be the (perhaps unforeseen) consequences or ramifications of 
      such a plan? How could those ``side effects'' be mitigated?
      
\item Examine your use of in-home appliances and resources. 
      Do you leave lights on? 
      Leave the water running when you brush your teeth? 
      Wash dishes by hand? 
      Leave computers or entertainment systems in ``standby'' mode when not in use?
      (See the concepts of ``phantom,'' ``vampire,'' or standby load). 
      Why do you do these things?
      Does your home have a second (or third) refrigerator or freezer?
      Why?
      What would it take for you to change your behavior?
      
\item Notice that biomass heating (that is, wood) does not appear in 
      Figure~\ref{fig:AverageHouseholdEnergyConsumption}. However, 
      RECS Table CE 7.2 reports that wood heated 12.5 million housing units in
      2015 (10.6\% of all housing units) and was 5.6\% of all BTUs used for
      household heating. 
      (For around 60\% of housing units wood is the main source of heat;
      for the other 40\% it's secondary.)
      % Pre-1950s houses are most likely to use wood heat.
      Wood heating can be carbon neutral. 
      However, wood heating isn't exactly sustainable. 
      It is sustainable \emph{only} if not everyone does it. 
      If everyone heated with wood, one result would be massive deforestation.
      Another might be greatly increased air pollution (in the form of soot).
      Should the use of wood heating be expanded or contracted? 
      Who gets to (or has to) heat with wood and what emissions should be permitted?
      How should such questions be decided?
      What other considerations go into wood heating? 
      For example, who has access to forest lands? How much does wood cost?
      What labor is required to obtain and use wood for heat?
      
\item Figure~\ref{fig:AverageHouseholdEnergyConsumption} also excludes ``district
      steam'' and solar thermal heat sources. Should such sources be promoted
      for sustainability? What considerations affect their more widespread adoption?
      
\item This chapter discussed energy efficiency measures for many of the categories
      featured in Figure \ref{fig:average_residential_energy}, such as AFUE, SEER
      rating, and Energy Star labels. 
      However, some categories of household appliances do not have an efficiency rating. 
      What are some appliances that \emph{could} be rated that are not?
      (See, for instance, \url{https://www.energystar.gov/productfinder/}.)
      Household vacuum cleaners, for example, are difficult to rate, in part, because defining 
      how \emph{well} they do their job (that is, the ``numerator'' of an efficacy
      metric) is difficult.
      (See the Energy Star \emph{Market and Industry Scoping Report
      on Vacuum Cleaners}, November 2011.)
      
\item Should product longevity be factored into consumer-oriented energy efficiency
      ratings? If so, how? 
      Do you think a vacuum cleaner that lasts 10 years is better
      than a vacuum cleaner that lasts only 5 years? Under what conditions or
      assumptions?
      
\item Should consumer appliances and household goods be required to contribute to a circular economy?
      If so, under what conditions or which appliances? 
      Should electronics recycling be mandatory?
      
\item One thing that you can do to make your housing unit more energy efficient
      is to eat every meal at a restaurant. Think of all energy you will save!
      No need for freezers, refrigeration, cooking, or dish washing. 
      Figure~\ref{fig:average_residential_energy} shows these categories
      are 10.4\% of the energy use of an average household.
      What is wrong with this analysis?
      Under what circumstances could it be correct?
      Are there opportunities to improve sustainability by outsourcing other 
      household tasks like laundry, or house cleaning? If so, what are they?

\end{questions}


