      Rank the costs of the windows.

\item If you are a college or university student,
      write a letter to yourself that describes
      the future household in which you want to live.
      What is the size of the dwelling?
      What are its sustainability features?

\item Investigate energy retrofitting and recomissioning for buildings.
      What is the purpose of these activities?
      How do they contribute to sustainability?
      What would be the effect on household emissions if every home in the U.S.\
      were retrofitted with higher-efficiency appliances and more insulation?
      
\item With reference to question Q\ref{chap:households}.\ref{question:household_policies},
      make a sustainability-related benefits/drawbacks ledger for each policy, 
      being sure to identify areas where sustainability would be enhanced and 
      places where sustainability would be diminished.
      Be sure to address all three corners of the sustainability triangle, 
      social, environmental, and monetary.
      After creating the ledger, 
      rethink your initial reactions to the policies.
      Now which policies would you welcome?
      Which would you resist?
      Why?
      
      For example, if all clothes washing were to be done at laundromats, 
      there could be social benefits where laundromats would become a sort of ``town square''
      where neighbors meet to discuss municipal affairs as they do their laundry.
      On the other hand, time lost to commuting to the laundromat might mean that other relationships suffer.
      If all clothes were laundered at laundromats, 
      fewer washers and dryers would be needed, resulting in less energy and CO$_2$ embodied 
      in the stock of laundry equipment.
      But laundromats will likely have larger commercial washers and dryers. 
      Would they be less energy efficient than smaller domestic washers and dryers?
      Many people will need to drive to laundromats to do laundry, increasing transport-related
      CO$_2$ emissions.
      Finally, households would no longer purchase washers and dryers, thereby saving money. 
      But the marginal cost of a load of laundry may be higher at a laundromat compared 
      to home-based laundry. 
      Is it a long-term financial benefit to do all your laundry at a laundromat? 
      How does the financial calculus change when the financial value of time is considered?
      
\item Cascade (a Proctor \& Gamble brand and a manufacturer of automatic dishwasher
      detergent) did a study that shows it takes an average
      person 15 seconds to wash a dish ``by hand.'' Assuming an average water flow
      from the faucet of two gallons per minute and an Energy Star automatic dishwasher
      using 4 gallons of water per cycle, Cascade concluded that it is more
      efficient to run the dishwasher with only eight dishes than to wash them by hand.
      (Note they were not advocating running near-empty loads, only that the break-even
      point was a very low number of dishes.)
      Measure your sink's flow rate and time yourself washing a variety of types of dishes.
      What is your break-even point?
      What is your break-even point for buying a new dishwasher?
      
\end{projects}



